more detail in a few minutes,

25
00:01:20.579 --> 00:01:23.816
and the other is the
Maturity Modeling Subcommittee.

26
00:01:23.849 --> 00:01:27.553
So part of Silver will contain
a maturity model where you can

27
00:01:27.586 --> 00:01:31.257
figure out where the
organization is doing well at

28
00:01:31.290 --> 00:01:33.726
maturity and where you
need a little bit of work.

29
00:01:33.759 --> 00:01:38.464
And that program is set to
scale from one-person consulting

30
00:01:38.497 --> 00:01:41.300
companies, all the way up
through companies the size

31
00:01:41.333 --> 00:01:45.771
of VMware, and universities
and government organizations.

32
00:01:45.804 --> 00:01:50.209
So with that introduction,
I'm going to go ahead

33
00:01:50.242 --> 00:01:52.345
and get started.

34
00:01:52.378 --> 00:01:55.615
So first, I'm going to assume
that you guys don't really know

35
00:01:55.648 --> 00:01:58.484
anything about W3C, and I'm
going to take us through

36
00:01:58.517 --> 00:02:00.486
an accessibility timeline.

37
00:02:00.519 --> 00:02:04.757
It's like how did we get here,
where we are today and what is

38
00:02:04.790 --> 00:02:06.392
it that we know is pending.

39
00:02:06.425 --> 00:02:09.729
I'm going to talk a little
bit about general WordPress

40
00:02:09.762 --> 00:02:11.831
accessibility advice.

41
00:02:11.864 --> 00:02:15.301
I'll talk about the guidelines
in the WCAG that are going to be

42
00:02:15.334 --> 00:02:19.705
updated in the next release, and
also the new guidelines that

43
00:02:19.738 --> 00:02:21.541
are pending.

44
00:02:21.574 --> 00:02:23.509
So first of all, the timeline.

45
00:02:23.542 --> 00:02:31.117
So accessibility started before
2006 but it really hit the map

46
00:02:31.150 --> 00:02:33.052
on 2006.

47
00:02:33.085 --> 00:02:36.355
I can't believe it's been 14
years since the Target lawsuit.

48
00:02:36.388 --> 00:02:39.625
So the Target lawsuit was
the first lawsuit in the

49
00:02:39.658 --> 00:02:43.062
United States, we are a
very litigious country,

50
00:02:43.095 --> 00:02:46.365
that went all the way
to a written ruling.

51
00:02:46.398 --> 00:02:50.536
And the written ruling was yes,
websites have to be accessible.

52
00:02:50.569 --> 00:02:55.641
And coincidently, that's also
around the time where

53
00:02:55.674 --> 00:02:57.543
WCAG 1.0 came out.

54
00:02:57.576 --> 00:03:01.280
At the end of 2008,
WCAG 2.0 came out.

55
00:03:01.313 --> 00:03:05.585
So what happened around
the same time as WCAG 2.0?

56
00:03:05.618 --> 00:03:07.186
iPhones.

57
00:03:07.219 --> 00:03:12.358
So there were no mobile specific
guidelines in WCAG 2.0 because

58
00:03:12.391 --> 00:03:16.762
mobile and native apps really
weren't a thing when WCAG 2.0

59
00:03:16.795 --> 00:03:18.431
was released.

60
00:03:18.464 --> 00:03:23.336
So then we had kind of a long
gap where of about ten years.

61
00:03:23.369 --> 00:03:28.307
And then in the summer of
2018, WCAG 2.1 was released,

62
00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:32.445
so this was plus or
minus two years ago.

63
00:03:32.478 --> 00:03:36.616
And also Section 508
merged with WCAG 2.0,

64
00:03:36.649 --> 00:03:38.317
which was the older version.

65
00:03:38.350 --> 00:03:41.854
So Section 508 is the public
sector purchasing rules in

66
00:03:41.887 --> 00:03:43.088
the United States.

67
00:03:43.122 --> 00:03:46.192
And in the United States, the
definition of the public sector

68
00:03:46.225 --> 00:03:51.163
is anybody who's spending
federal money either directly

69
00:03:51.196 --> 00:03:52.498
or indirectly.

70
00:03:52.531 --> 00:03:54.867
So that includes
things like, you know,

71
00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:57.503
government organizations,
the military,

72
00:03:57.536 --> 00:04:01.173
health and human
services, the TSA.

73
00:04:01.206 --> 00:04:05.578
But it also includes people
who get money from the feds.

74
00:04:05.611 --> 00:04:08.748
So it's anybody who's spending
Medicaid and Medicare money,

75
00:04:08.781 --> 00:04:10.483
which is hospitals.

76
00:04:10.516 --> 00:04:14.520
It's anybody that's in any type
of publicly supported schools,

77
00:04:14.553 --> 00:04:18.658
all the way from
preschool head start programs,

78
00:04:18.691 --> 00:04:22.061
all the way up through
public graduate programs

79
00:04:22.094 --> 00:04:23.629
in universities.

80
00:04:23.662 --> 00:04:25.331
It's all the states.

81
00:04:25.364 --> 00:04:27.266
It's all the municipalities.

82
00:04:27.299 --> 00:04:31.504
It's the civil service,
the post office,

83
00:04:31.537 --> 00:04:34.740
the court systems,
the police systems.

84
00:04:34.773 --> 00:04:36.742
Everything I just
identified there,

85
00:04:36.775 --> 00:04:38.844
comes under Section 508.

86
00:04:38.877 --> 00:04:44.250
And there are rules in 508 that say
you can't buy anything that's

87
00:04:44.283 --> 00:04:47.153
not compliant with WCAG 2.0.

88
00:04:47.186 --> 00:04:54.126
Now, unfortunately, for the 16
years that 508 had existed up

89
00:04:54.159 --> 00:04:57.496
until that point, because it had
its own standard previously that

90
00:04:57.529 --> 00:05:00.199
also said things
had to be accessible,

91
00:05:00.232 --> 00:05:02.435
but it was being
measured in a different way,

92
00:05:02.468 --> 00:05:07.807
508 was more known for
people not following the rules,

93
00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:10.109
then following the rules.

94
00:05:10.142 --> 00:05:14.714
So, in 2019, September 23rd,
the EU had its stop sell

95
00:05:14.747 --> 00:05:17.383
web soft deadline.

96
00:05:17.416 --> 00:05:20.052
And what that meant is any
software that was released after

97
00:05:20.085 --> 00:05:24.190
this date that was going to
be public facing had to be

98
00:05:24.223 --> 00:05:27.426
accessible or the EU
governments wouldn't buy it.

99
00:05:27.459 --> 00:05:32.298
So again, the United States is
very litigious so what happened?

100
00:05:32.331 --> 00:05:37.236
People who have disabilities
started suing companies who

101
00:05:37.269 --> 00:05:39.405
weren't complying with WCAG 2.0.

102
00:05:39.438 --> 00:05:43.309
And we've had 4600
lawsuits in the last two years.

103
00:05:43.342 --> 00:05:47.713
Looking at the 2020 trends, it
might've dropped a little bit,

104
00:05:47.746 --> 00:05:51.617
but only because the courthouses
were closed for three months

105
00:05:51.650 --> 00:05:54.186
for nonemergency
cases in most states.

106
00:05:54.219 --> 00:05:59.191
And so, the trends now are back
up to where they were

107
00:05:59.224 --> 00:06:01.093
in 2018 and 2019.

108
00:06:01.126 --> 00:06:05.698
2020 will be a little bit lower
overall but only because of

109
00:06:05.731 --> 00:06:09.502
COVID, not because filing
lawsuits is slowing down

110
00:06:09.535 --> 00:06:12.338
for accessibility.

111
00:06:12.371 --> 00:06:15.474
So initially it was the public
that was suing

112
00:06:15.507 --> 00:06:17.209
over accessibility.

113
00:06:17.242 --> 00:06:19.345
"I can't buy my Beyonce goods."

114
00:06:19.378 --> 00:06:22.014
"I can't buy my NBA tickets.

115
00:06:22.047 --> 00:06:25.818
Now, what's happening is
employees are suing employers

116
00:06:25.851 --> 00:06:32.124
for disability discrimination
over inaccessibility.

117
00:06:32.157 --> 00:06:34.527
"I couldn't get this job.

118
00:06:34.560 --> 00:06:36.796
I couldn't get this transfer
because you choose to buy

119
00:06:36.829 --> 00:06:38.597
inaccessible software."

120
00:06:38.630 --> 00:06:41.767
So putting the pressure on
companies not only to build

121
00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:45.738
accessible software but to
buy accessible software.

122
00:06:45.771 --> 00:06:51.076
Okay, we just passed the
stop sell firm deadline

123
00:06:51.109 --> 00:06:53.546
for the EU in 2020.

124
00:06:53.579 --> 00:06:56.182
That was September
23rd, which was,

125
00:06:56.215 --> 00:06:58.818
you know, a little over
a week and a half ago.

126
00:06:58.851 --> 00:07:01.320
You are here so that's where
we are with respect to this

127
00:07:01.353 --> 00:07:03.422
accessibility timeline.

128
00:07:03.455 --> 00:07:09.595
In 2021, in Canada,
AODA, in particular,

129
00:07:09.628 --> 00:07:16.001
A-O-D-A, 2.0 AA will
kick in January 1st.

130
00:07:16.034 --> 00:07:19.472
Up until now, Canada in Ontario
has only been required to meet

131
00:07:19.505 --> 00:07:25.444
WCAG 2.0, and the native app
piece of the European Union

132
00:07:25.477 --> 00:07:28.514
legislation will
be taking effect.

133
00:07:28.547 --> 00:07:34.820
And then finally, the
AG 3.0 Project Silver.

134
00:07:34.853 --> 00:07:37.523
And let me explain
what that means.

135
00:07:37.556 --> 00:07:40.526
So WCAG accessibility
guidelines W-C-A-G,

136
00:07:40.559 --> 00:07:42.561
it's a bit of a misnomer.

137
00:07:42.594 --> 00:07:45.297
The WC is for web content,
but the guidelines are

138
00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:48.367
for any software.

139
00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:51.203
It's for native app software
whether it runs on mobile or on

140
00:07:51.236 --> 00:07:53.606
a desktop platform.

141
00:07:53.639 --> 00:07:57.409
It's for HTML-based
software that uses the web.

142
00:07:57.442 --> 00:07:59.478
It's also for documentation.

143
00:07:59.511 --> 00:08:05.401
So originally, they decided to
drop the WC from WCAG and just

144
00:08:05.401 --> 00:08:08.087
call it AG:
Accessibility Guidelines.

145
00:08:08.120 --> 00:08:11.390
For those of you who remember
your high school chemistry,

146
00:08:11.423 --> 00:08:15.094
AG is the periodic
symbol for silver.

147
00:08:15.127 --> 00:08:18.731
And so that's how this ended
up being called Project Silver.

148
00:08:18.764 --> 00:08:23.068
Another thing that's coming
out in 2022 is the

149
00:08:23.101 --> 00:08:24.436
European Accessibility Act.

150
00:08:24.469 --> 00:08:27.806
That will be the
first extension,

151
00:08:27.839 --> 00:08:31.010
in terms of adoption by
the EU member states,

152
00:08:31.043 --> 00:08:36.215
where each EU member state will
had to have locally adopted

153
00:08:36.248 --> 00:08:39.151
the pending European
Accessibility Act,

154
00:08:39.184 --> 00:08:40.719
and then the European
Accessibility Act

155
00:08:40.752 --> 00:08:43.489
will be final in 2025.

156
00:08:43.522 --> 00:08:49.628
And that will include websites
regardless of whether or not

157
00:08:49.661 --> 00:08:51.730
they're public facing, so
it will be all websites,

158
00:08:51.763 --> 00:08:56.235
and it also includes
products that have hardware

159
00:08:56.268 --> 00:08:57.670
components to them.

160
00:08:57.703 --> 00:09:01.473
So the European Accessibility
Act is much broader than EN

161
00:09:01.506 --> 00:09:09.682
301549, which had these stop
sell deadlines in 2019 and 2020,

162
00:09:09.715 --> 00:09:12.751
and then for the web,
and then the apps

163
00:09:12.784 --> 00:09:14.787
kicking in, in 2021.

164
00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:20.059
So this is a "how did we get
here" and "where is it that

165
00:09:20.092 --> 00:09:21.727
we know that we're going."

166
00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:25.598
So what's going to be part of
all of these W3C guidelines?

167
00:09:25.631 --> 00:09:29.602
Well, first of all, I want
to talk a little bit about

168
00:09:29.635 --> 00:09:32.805
WordPress accessibility, and
this may have already been

169
00:09:32.838 --> 00:09:35.040
discussed in
previous conversations,

170
00:09:35.073 --> 00:09:37.443
so I won't take too
long to go through it.

171
00:09:37.476 --> 00:09:40.346
But they are a bunch of
accessible templates out there.

172
00:09:40.379 --> 00:09:44.156
There are accessible
plugins out there.

173
00:09:44.156 --> 00:09:46.619
If you take an accessible
template and you put

174
00:09:46.652 --> 00:09:49.688
an inaccessible plugin in it,
you've just broke accessibility.

175
00:09:49.721 --> 00:09:54.026
So the entire experience
needs to be accessible.

176
00:09:54.059 --> 00:09:56.795
It's not just enough for the
template to be accessible.

177
00:09:56.828 --> 00:10:00.833
Things that commonly used
with WordPress that are mostly

178
00:10:00.866 --> 00:10:05.437
accessible, but you have to make
sure that you implement them in

179
00:10:05.470 --> 00:10:08.707
an accessible manner are
Microsoft and Google forms,

180
00:10:08.740 --> 00:10:13.312
SurveyMonkey, Mailchimp,
Qualtrics and SurveyGizmo.

181
00:10:13.345 --> 00:10:16.115
Lots, and lots and
lots of survey systems,

182
00:10:16.148 --> 00:10:19.752
especially survey systems that
are designed to go with design

183
00:10:19.785 --> 00:10:24.390
tools, those tend
to be inaccessible.

184
00:10:24.423 --> 00:10:28.527
It's the standalone survey
systems that occasionally

185
00:10:28.560 --> 00:10:30.195
are accessible.

186
00:10:30.228 --> 00:10:32.865
But you need to check these
things because if you implement,

187
00:10:32.898 --> 00:10:36.402
for example, Hotjar, on
an inaccessible--sorry.

188
00:10:36.435 --> 00:10:40.506
You implement Hotjar on
top of an accessible system,

189
00:10:40.539 --> 00:10:43.742
Hotjar is inaccessible, that's
going to cause problems

190
00:10:43.775 --> 00:10:46.745
for your disabled users.

191
00:10:46.778 --> 00:10:49.682
Okay, so, as I said make sure
that your entire experience

192
00:10:49.715 --> 00:10:51.250
is accessible.

193
00:10:51.283 --> 00:10:53.485
That includes the
surveys, the communications,

194
00:10:53.518 --> 00:10:56.155
you want to have an
accessibility email address

195
00:10:56.188 --> 00:10:59.525
where people can send in
comments or complaints.

196
00:10:59.558 --> 00:11:03.462
You should have an accessibility
statement on your site.

197
00:11:03.495 --> 00:11:06.765
You need to make sure that
your customer support can handle

198
00:11:06.798 --> 00:11:11.170
people who are contacting you
using assistive technology.

199
00:11:11.203 --> 00:11:14.239
That usually means you want
to have two modes of customer

200
00:11:14.272 --> 00:11:18.043
support, one that's voice based;
one that's not voice based.

201
00:11:18.076 --> 00:11:20.579
At a minimum, if you're
a teeny, tiny company,

202
00:11:20.612 --> 00:11:23.749
email is going to be the most
accessible customer support.

203
00:11:23.782 --> 00:11:27.519
My deaf daughter will rarely
pick up the phone and call

204
00:11:27.552 --> 00:11:31.590
people through a relay service
because it's just too slow and

205
00:11:31.623 --> 00:11:33.792
aggravating for her.

206
00:11:33.825 --> 00:11:36.128
You want to make sure
your social media posts

207
00:11:36.161 --> 00:11:37.329
are accessible.

208
00:11:37.362 --> 00:11:40.632
That means use captioning and
described audio for your--

209
00:11:40.665 --> 00:11:44.536
any videos that you're
posting when necessary,

210
00:11:44.569 --> 00:11:47.406
but don't use an accessible
WordPress template and then

211
00:11:47.439 --> 00:11:49.708
partner it with
inaccessible vendors,

212
00:11:49.741 --> 00:11:52.578
because you can't call yourself
accessible anymore

213
00:11:52.611 --> 00:11:54.447
at that point.

214
00:11:55.014 --> 00:11:58.717
So the first thing that's
coming and it's already somewhat

215
00:11:58.750 --> 00:12:00.519
released is COGA.

216
00:12:00.552 --> 00:12:03.455
And COGA stands for
Cognitive Accessibility.

217
00:12:03.488 --> 00:12:06.191
So before I get
too far into COGA,

218
00:12:06.224 --> 00:12:09.661
I'm going to talk about the
W3C process overall

219
00:12:09.694 --> 00:12:11.497
for doing updates.

220
00:12:11.530 --> 00:12:14.500
First, they charter
a task force.

221
00:12:14.533 --> 00:12:17.603
And so, there is a
COGA Task Force.

222
00:12:17.636 --> 00:12:20.539
Every Task Force has a charter.

223
00:12:20.572 --> 00:12:23.142
That means it has a very
specific focus list of things

224
00:12:23.175 --> 00:12:28.280
that that Task Force is allowed
to research and published

225
00:12:28.313 --> 00:12:30.048
guidelines are.

226
00:12:30.081 --> 00:12:33.652
Then the second thing they
do, is they solicit volunteers.

227
00:12:33.685 --> 00:12:37.389
W3C is largely a
volunteer driven organization.

228
00:12:37.422 --> 00:12:40.192
There are some
permanent employees,

229
00:12:40.225 --> 00:12:42.594
but I would say
probably three quarters,

230
00:12:42.627 --> 00:12:45.564
if not more of every
Task Force is volunteers.

231
00:12:45.597 --> 00:12:48.634
You can join at any
time, and that is a hint.

232
00:12:48.667 --> 00:12:53.505
If you go to the W3C website,
you can set yourself up

233
00:12:53.538 --> 00:12:56.038
an account and you can request

234
00:12:56.038 --> 00:13:00.212
to volunteer for a particular 
Task Force.

235
00:13:00.245 --> 00:13:06.059
Then there is this, what seems
to be sometimes endless series

236
00:13:06.059 --> 00:13:09.154
of meetings that includes
drafting new guidelines,

237
00:13:09.187 --> 00:13:12.558
and in the end, there is a vote
amongst the Task Force to decide

238
00:13:12.591 --> 00:13:15.661
whether or not the guidelines
should be presented

239
00:13:15.694 --> 00:13:17.529
to the public.

240
00:13:17.562 --> 00:13:21.533
That is a system that was
set up because the groups,

241
00:13:21.566 --> 00:13:25.103
the Task Force are large enough
that you're not going to be able

242
00:13:25.136 --> 00:13:27.840
to make all the
people happy all the time.

243
00:13:27.873 --> 00:13:30.709
And everybody has
their own perspective.

244
00:13:30.742 --> 00:13:36.215
I am participating as a person
who works for a super large

245
00:13:36.248 --> 00:13:39.551
public sector--not--sorry,
not public sector.

246
00:13:39.584 --> 00:13:43.422
Super large private
sector tech company.

247
00:13:43.455 --> 00:13:47.259
Other people who belong to
the Task Force work for small

248
00:13:47.292 --> 00:13:51.063
consultant companies,
large consulting companies,

249
00:13:51.096 --> 00:13:53.498
accessibility-specific companies.

250
00:13:53.531 --> 00:13:57.669
We have people who
belong--who work for banks,

251
00:13:57.702 --> 00:14:00.505
who work for Google,
who work for Amazon.

252
00:14:00.538 --> 00:14:05.177
So there's a lot of different
voices on the Task Force and not

253
00:14:05.210 --> 00:14:08.146
everybody is going to be happy
with the end result all the

254
00:14:08.179 --> 00:14:10.549
time, which is
why there's a vote.

255
00:14:10.582 --> 00:14:14.186
Okay, so we repeat number three
as many times as necessary

256
00:14:14.219 --> 00:14:17.289
to get something that we feel
is good enough

257
00:14:17.322 --> 00:14:18.824
to release to the public.

258
00:14:18.857 --> 00:14:22.694
So right now, if you want to
join the Silver Task Force,

259
00:14:22.727 --> 00:14:26.164
you have to commit at least
six hours a week of time to the

260
00:14:26.197 --> 00:14:32.537
meetings that are happening and
the outside drafting homework

261
00:14:32.570 --> 00:14:37.209
that you may be assigned, after
you feel that your skills and

262
00:14:37.242 --> 00:14:40.445
your integration is at a
good enough level that you

263
00:14:40.478 --> 00:14:42.447
can participate in
some of that work.

264
00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:45.384
Okay, then what happens is
something called the

265
00:14:45.417 --> 00:14:47.853
First Public Working
Draft is released.

266
00:14:47.886 --> 00:14:51.123
Sometimes, additional
information is released as well.

267
00:14:51.156 --> 00:14:56.161
For example, there is a note
that's currently been published

268
00:14:56.194 --> 00:15:03.602
about the challenges of applying
the W3C guidelines to SAS,

269
00:15:03.635 --> 00:15:07.739
to cloud-based software that
don't have monolithic releases,

270
00:15:07.772 --> 00:15:10.709
that are releasing little,
teeny tiny updates all the time.

271
00:15:10.742 --> 00:15:14.680
So some things are notes
but some things are--there's

272
00:15:14.713 --> 00:15:18.150
definitely always a
First Public Working Draft.

273
00:15:18.183 --> 00:15:22.254
Then there's a comment period
where people can submit in the

274
00:15:22.287 --> 00:15:25.791
public, non-volunteers can
submit comments and we loop

275
00:15:25.824 --> 00:15:27.392
back to number three.

276
00:15:27.425 --> 00:15:29.594
So we take the comments,
we have more meetings,

277
00:15:29.627 --> 00:15:31.830
we decide whether or not
we're going to update what we

278
00:15:31.863 --> 00:15:34.533
published in the First Public
Working Draft and then

279
00:15:34.566 --> 00:15:36.268
we vote again.

280
00:15:36.301 --> 00:15:39.638
Once that is done, then we have
the Second Public Working Draft.

281
00:15:39.671 --> 00:15:43.809
So this will be an updated
version that contains comments

282
00:15:43.842 --> 00:15:48.213
integrated that were
decided to be included.

283
00:15:48.246 --> 00:15:51.183
You know, again,
a comment period,

284
00:15:51.216 --> 00:15:52.784
obtaining comments
from the public.

285
00:15:52.817 --> 00:15:54.453
Loop back to number three.

286
00:15:54.486 --> 00:15:57.289
So you can see lots, and
lots and lots of meetings.

287
00:15:57.322 --> 00:15:59.524
And then the
standard becomes final.

288
00:15:59.557 --> 00:16:04.663
So this is what we're working
on right now with WCAG 2.2,

289
00:16:04.696 --> 00:16:07.366
Silver and COGA.

290
00:16:07.399 --> 00:16:12.270
All three of those are in
the middle of these processes.

291
00:16:12.303 --> 00:16:16.108
And then after the
standard becomes final,

292
00:16:16.141 --> 00:16:20.612
it's outside of W3C's control,
but it does get incorporated

293
00:16:20.645 --> 00:16:23.081
into laws,
lawsuits and settlements.

294
00:16:23.114 --> 00:16:30.422
It took four months from the
time that WCAG 2.1 was released

295
00:16:30.455 --> 00:16:33.725
until we saw it in the
first settlement agreement,

296
00:16:33.758 --> 00:16:36.228
so that was really, really fast.

297
00:16:36.261 --> 00:16:40.599
Most of the time you'll see that
companies that are entering into

298
00:16:40.632 --> 00:16:43.435
settlement agreements
get about 18 months,

299
00:16:43.468 --> 00:16:47.139
from the time of the settlement
agreement was executed until

300
00:16:47.172 --> 00:16:50.308
they have to be compliant
with what's in

301
00:16:50.341 --> 00:16:51.509
the settlement agreement.

302
00:16:51.542 --> 00:16:56.081
But it can be shorter because
the settlements are purely

303
00:16:56.114 --> 00:16:59.384
within the control of the
company that got sued and

304
00:16:59.417 --> 00:17:02.587
the people who sued them,
the plaintiffs and the

305
00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:04.689
defendants, effectively.

306
00:17:04.722 --> 00:17:07.559
Okay, so looking at the
Cognitive Accessibility

307
00:17:07.592 --> 00:17:11.396
Task Force, it's a joint Task
Force between the Accessible

308
00:17:11.429 --> 00:17:14.332
Platform Architectures Group
and the Silver Group,

309
00:17:14.365 --> 00:17:16.635
the Web content
accessibility guidelines.

310
00:17:16.668 --> 00:17:18.570
We call that AG WG.

311
00:17:18.603 --> 00:17:23.241
So they are producing a
whole ton of documentation,

312
00:17:23.274 --> 00:17:28.313
and guidance documents, and
research and updating all W3C

313
00:17:28.346 --> 00:17:32.350
material that addresses issues
that are in the cognitive space.

314
00:17:32.383 --> 00:17:34.719
So what's in the
cognitive space?

315
00:17:34.752 --> 00:17:39.391
The cognitive space includes
things like neurodiversity.

316
00:17:39.424 --> 00:17:41.760
So that would be
attention deficit disorder,

317
00:17:41.793 --> 00:17:50.168
dyslexia, dyscalculia, anything
related to autism or Asperger's.

318
00:17:50.201 --> 00:17:53.538
It also includes
traumatic brain injury.

319
00:17:53.571 --> 00:17:58.276
It includes memory loss.
It includes dementia.

320
00:17:58.309 --> 00:18:03.181
Basically anything
that your brain,

321
00:18:03.214 --> 00:18:07.385
where it might not be
functioning at 100% either

322
00:18:07.418 --> 00:18:11.790
for temporary reasons such
as situational depression,

323
00:18:11.823 --> 00:18:16.094
for example, or
chemotherapy side effects,

324
00:18:16.127 --> 00:18:18.797
all the way to
permanent disabilities.

325
00:18:18.830 --> 00:18:21.800
And the permanent disabilities
can either be acquired

326
00:18:21.833 --> 00:18:23.735
such as traumatic brain injury.

327
00:18:23.768 --> 00:18:26.138
That's always an acquired
disability or they can be

328
00:18:26.171 --> 00:18:28.707
congenital like Down syndrome.

329
00:18:28.740 --> 00:18:31.243
And I have put in a link.

330
00:18:31.276 --> 00:18:33.678
Everything that you see that's
blue and underlined in this

331
00:18:33.711 --> 00:18:34.912
deck is a link.

332
00:18:34.946 --> 00:18:39.818
And so, that is the link to
the current COGA publication,

333
00:18:39.851 --> 00:18:42.420
and the current
COGA publication,

334
00:18:42.453 --> 00:18:47.592
in turn, is being used to inform
new guidelines that are going

335
00:18:47.625 --> 00:18:55.133
into WCAG 2.2 and
Silver WCAG 3.0.

336
00:18:55.166 --> 00:18:57.636
Okay, sorry, I got a little
bit ahead of myself.

337
00:18:57.669 --> 00:19:03.441
So this is what disabilities
does focus--does COGA focus on.

338
00:19:03.474 --> 00:19:05.210
Aphasia.

339
00:19:05.243 --> 00:19:07.245
I always forget that one.

340
00:19:07.278 --> 00:19:11.416
So that's my own
cognitive issue.

341
00:19:11.449 --> 00:19:17.289
So these are the lists of all
the disability that COGA covers.

342
00:19:17.322 --> 00:19:20.692
What types of guidelines
is COGA going to bring us.

343
00:19:20.725 --> 00:19:25.230
First of all, there are a series
of plain language requirements.

344
00:19:25.263 --> 00:19:29.034
You want to make sure that
you're using language

345
00:19:29.067 --> 00:19:30.502
in your website.

346
00:19:30.535 --> 00:19:33.605
So content, for all
intents and purposes,

347
00:19:33.638 --> 00:19:36.741
that is at the
level of your reader.

348
00:19:36.774 --> 00:19:40.545
And when it's beyond
the level of your reader,

349
00:19:40.578 --> 00:19:43.381
you want to make sure that
you're linking to definitions

350
00:19:43.414 --> 00:19:45.750
that your reader
can find easily.

351
00:19:45.783 --> 00:19:49.354
So, for example, the word
dyscalculia is not super well

352
00:19:49.387 --> 00:19:55.126
known to most people with 6th
to 8th grade reading levels,

353
00:19:55.159 --> 00:19:58.430
so you would want to have a link
whenever you use that word in

354
00:19:58.463 --> 00:20:01.266
your website, if it was
included in your website,

355
00:20:01.299 --> 00:20:03.368
to a definition where
somebody could read,

356
00:20:03.401 --> 00:20:06.204
"Oh, this is what
dyscalculia means."

357
00:20:06.237 --> 00:20:09.274
The second type of groups of
guidelines that COGA will bring

358
00:20:09.307 --> 00:20:12.110
us, is clear purpose
requirements,

359
00:20:12.143 --> 00:20:15.680
making it obvious to the users
what it is that they're supposed

360
00:20:15.713 --> 00:20:18.850
to be doing and what steps
they're going to be taking.

361
00:20:18.883 --> 00:20:22.387
You know, basically telling
the user what the happy path is.

362
00:20:22.420 --> 00:20:26.625
And the third set of
requirements that are coming are

363
00:20:26.658 --> 00:20:30.629
the need to be able to operate
without having good memory.

364
00:20:30.662 --> 00:20:34.366
So leaving more breadcrumbs
for your users to figure out

365
00:20:34.399 --> 00:20:37.469
how they got to where they are,
and more importantly,

366
00:20:37.502 --> 00:20:43.141
how to get back to where they
are when they don't--when they

367
00:20:43.174 --> 00:20:45.877
forget things quickly, where
they don't have good

368
00:20:45.910 --> 00:20:47.545
working short-term memory.

369
00:20:47.578 --> 00:20:50.715
So those are the three different
categories that are--of

370
00:20:50.748 --> 00:20:53.251
guidelines that are
currently pending,

371
00:20:53.284 --> 00:20:56.421
and I'll get into more specifics
about what we know about what

372
00:20:56.454 --> 00:21:03.028
WCAG 2.2 and 3.0 that include
instances of these types

373
00:21:03.061 --> 00:21:05.664
of guidelines.

374
00:21:05.697 --> 00:21:07.332
Okay.

375
00:21:07.365 --> 00:21:10.635
So now, moving out of
COGA and onto WCAG 2.2.

376
00:21:10.668 --> 00:21:16.608
So WCAG 2.2 is currently--has
its Second Public Working

377
00:21:16.641 --> 00:21:18.410
Draft out.

378
00:21:18.443 --> 00:21:19.644
It is still a work in progress.

379
00:21:19.678 --> 00:21:23.348
What we're about to talk about
is still subject to change,

380
00:21:23.381 --> 00:21:25.717
but it's getting towards final.

381
00:21:25.750 --> 00:21:29.120
Originally, it was planned
to be final in November.

382
00:21:29.153 --> 00:21:32.357
That got delayed a little bit
because of COVID,

383
00:21:32.390 --> 00:21:37.195
and we're looking at WCAG 2.2
becoming final in approximately

384
00:21:37.228 --> 00:21:39.297
June of next year.

385
00:21:39.330 --> 00:21:41.566
So that's June of 2021.

386
00:21:41.599 --> 00:21:47.639
And if you add the standard 18
months to when--that 18 months

387
00:21:47.672 --> 00:21:51.176
is not a W3C you have
to implement this in

388
00:21:51.209 --> 00:21:52.811
18 months guideline.

389
00:21:52.844 --> 00:21:58.149
That 18 months is a somewhat
safe buffer range that we have

390
00:21:58.182 --> 00:22:03.321
seen in the United States, where
once a standard becomes final,

391
00:22:03.354 --> 00:22:06.391
if you implant that standard
within the next 18 months,

392
00:22:06.424 --> 00:22:09.728
chances are you won't get sued.

393
00:22:09.761 --> 00:22:17.135
So that means 18 months
from June of 2021,

394
00:22:17.168 --> 00:22:21.639
takes us either to the end of
2022 or the beginning of 2023,

395
00:22:21.672 --> 00:22:25.210
that you would have to
have these nine new standards

396
00:22:25.243 --> 00:22:31.616
implemented by, in order to be
relatively safe from lawsuits.

397
00:22:31.649 --> 00:22:34.819
I'm kind of using
some fudging words here,

398
00:22:34.852 --> 00:22:39.624
because of course, you can
sued for WCAG 2.2 noncompliance,

399
00:22:39.657 --> 00:22:42.093
the day after comes out.

400
00:22:42.126 --> 00:22:44.529
But that's not
really reasonable, but

401
00:22:44.562 --> 00:22:49.868
reasonable doesn't always factor
into United States litigation.

402
00:22:49.901 --> 00:22:54.239
So 18 months is typically the
amount of time before you start

403
00:22:54.272 --> 00:22:59.177
to see the new standards
reflected in laws and lawsuits.

404
00:22:59.210 --> 00:23:04.449
Okay, so there are nine
guidelines, new guidelines that

405
00:23:04.482 --> 00:23:07.585
pertain to WCAG 2.2.

406
00:23:07.618 --> 00:23:12.223
Eight of them are A and AA.

407
00:23:12.256 --> 00:23:14.759
Some I'm not going to
cover the AAA guideline.

408
00:23:14.792 --> 00:23:17.462
I have a link to it in
the references section.

409
00:23:17.495 --> 00:23:21.633
But typically, people don't
implement AAA guidelines.

410
00:23:21.666 --> 00:23:24.369
They're fairly restrictive,
especially with respect

411
00:23:24.402 --> 00:23:27.172
to colors, the AAA
guidelines in general.

412
00:23:27.205 --> 00:23:31.609
And in the U.S., in particular,
AA is the standard that

413
00:23:31.642 --> 00:23:34.212
everybody seems to have adopted.

414
00:23:34.245 --> 00:23:39.751
So the focus here will be on the
eight new guidelines that are

415
00:23:39.784 --> 00:23:42.187
either A or AA.

416
00:23:42.220 --> 00:23:45.123
And you can see I've mentioned
in the link in each of these

417
00:23:45.156 --> 00:23:48.393
slides, whether it's an A
or double A requirement.

418
00:23:48.426 --> 00:23:52.263
So the first new
guideline is Focus Appearance.

419
00:23:52.296 --> 00:23:56.100
So this guideline is related to
two other guidelines pertaining

420
00:23:56.133 --> 00:23:58.570
to keyboard focus indicators.

421
00:23:58.603 --> 00:24:03.141
One of the guidelines is 2.4.7,
which is that you have to have

422
00:24:03.174 --> 00:24:04.609
a focus that's visible.

423
00:24:04.642 --> 00:24:08.580
And one of the changes in
WCAG 2.2 is that guideline

424
00:24:08.613 --> 00:24:12.750
in particular, is
moving from AA to A.

425
00:24:12.783 --> 00:24:16.421
So A is the dealbreakers.

426
00:24:16.454 --> 00:24:19.090
If you don't do this, you're
making it not work for a whole

427
00:24:19.123 --> 00:24:21.426
ton of people with disabilities.

428
00:24:21.459 --> 00:24:23.528
AA is you're making it hard.

429
00:24:23.561 --> 00:24:25.797
So that's kind of the
distinction between the two.

430
00:24:25.830 --> 00:24:31.402
So the other guideline that this
is referencing is 1.4.11 which

431
00:24:31.435 --> 00:24:33.271
is Non-text Contrast.

432
00:24:33.304 --> 00:24:36.441
So all three of these combined
relate to how you treat

433
00:24:36.474 --> 00:24:40.411
keyboard focus indicators
for actionable objects.

434
00:24:40.444 --> 00:24:41.645
Okay.

435
00:24:41.679 --> 00:24:45.350
So the summation of all three
of the guidelines put together,

436
00:24:45.383 --> 00:24:47.819
so not just the new one,
but all three of them,

437
00:24:47.852 --> 00:24:50.822
you have to have a
keyboard focus indicator.

438
00:24:50.855 --> 00:24:52.624
Nonnegotiable.

439
00:24:52.657 --> 00:24:55.326
That comes from 2.4.7,
which as I mentioned,

440
00:24:55.359 --> 00:24:59.697
is moving from AA to A, in
terms of requirement level.

441
00:24:59.730 --> 00:25:05.603
Keyboard focus indicator has to
have a contrast of 3.0 to 1.0

442
00:25:05.636 --> 00:25:06.771
at all times.

443
00:25:06.804 --> 00:25:13.077
That comes from 1.4.11,
which came out with WCAG 2.1.

444
00:25:13.110 --> 00:25:18.149
And then finally, the focus
indication area has to be

445
00:25:18.182 --> 00:25:19.484
thick enough to be able to see.

446
00:25:19.517 --> 00:25:22.654
So, the first requirement in
2.0 was you have to have

447
00:25:22.687 --> 00:25:24.222
an indicator.

448
00:25:24.255 --> 00:25:26.558
The second requirement
in 2.1 was,

449
00:25:26.591 --> 00:25:29.460
"Oh yeah, you have to be
able to see the indicator.

450
00:25:29.493 --> 00:25:31.563
You have to have
enough contrast."

451
00:25:31.596 --> 00:25:35.366
The addition that they've made
in WCAG 2.2 is you really have

452
00:25:35.399 --> 00:25:37.468
to see the indicator.

453
00:25:37.501 --> 00:25:39.737
So it added an
aspect of thickness.

454
00:25:39.770 --> 00:25:43.341
So it either has to be at least
8 CSS pixels on the short side

455
00:25:43.374 --> 00:25:47.779
or it has to be 1 CSS
pixel all the way around.

456
00:25:47.812 --> 00:25:49.747
You can't make it
any smaller than that.

457
00:25:49.780 --> 00:25:52.450
You really don't
want to make it dashed.

458
00:25:52.483 --> 00:25:55.119
Okay, so people have
gotten creative in trying to be

459
00:25:55.152 --> 00:25:59.824
compliant without--compliant
with the letter of the guideline

460
00:25:59.857 --> 00:26:03.628
without being compliant with
the spirit of the guideline.

461
00:26:03.661 --> 00:26:08.266
Spirit of the guideline was
people like me with glaucoma who

462
00:26:08.299 --> 00:26:11.235
are keyboard-only users, need to
be able to see the darn keyboard

463
00:26:11.268 --> 00:26:12.503
focus indicator.

464
00:26:12.536 --> 00:26:16.374
Because people were trying to
skirt that by making keyboard

465
00:26:16.407 --> 00:26:20.445
focus indicators, you know,
light blue or yellow,

466
00:26:20.478 --> 00:26:23.748
so that, you know, the designers
just didn't want it to impact

467
00:26:23.781 --> 00:26:27.452
what the website looked like.

468
00:26:27.485 --> 00:26:30.655
So then we added the
darkness requirements,

469
00:26:30.688 --> 00:26:31.856
the contrast requirements.

470
00:26:31.889 --> 00:26:35.693
Then designers tried to use
fancy patterns to again make it

471
00:26:35.726 --> 00:26:41.065
not so visible, and so now the
guidelines have specific rules

472
00:26:41.098 --> 00:26:43.201
about thickness.

473
00:26:43.234 --> 00:26:46.504
So that is the first new
guideline that's coming with

474
00:26:46.537 --> 00:26:51.409
2.2, and also the
related change to 2.1,

475
00:26:51.442 --> 00:26:55.346
making the keyboard focus
indicator requirement

476
00:26:55.379 --> 00:26:58.383
moving from AA to A.

477
00:26:58.416 --> 00:27:00.018
Okay.

478
00:27:00.051 --> 00:27:02.687
And then finally, the keyboard
focus indicator can never be

479
00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:04.622
blocked by content.

480
00:27:04.655 --> 00:27:09.394
You'll see that that is a
trend that started in WCAG 2.1,

481
00:27:09.427 --> 00:27:15.033
with guidelines pertaining to
popovers and it's been extended

482
00:27:15.066 --> 00:27:18.336
into over the
keyboard focus indicator,

483
00:27:18.369 --> 00:27:22.040
that you can't block a keyboard
focus indicator with a popover

484
00:27:22.073 --> 00:27:25.143
or with a dialog
box or something,

485
00:27:25.176 --> 00:27:28.646
that's just going to make it
really hard for the

486
00:27:28.679 --> 00:27:32.583
keyboard user to
be able to see it.

487
00:27:32.616 --> 00:27:37.388
The next guideline that's being
added is what are called

488
00:27:37.421 --> 00:27:39.390
Fixed Reference Points.

489
00:27:39.423 --> 00:27:43.728
So--and you'll see that most of
these guidelines' additions come

490
00:27:43.761 --> 00:27:48.132
from pain points So the
pain point for 2.4.11,

491
00:27:48.165 --> 00:27:50.101
which is the one that
we just talked about,

492
00:27:50.134 --> 00:27:54.405
is keyboard-only users
who use magnification.

493
00:27:54.438 --> 00:27:58.643
The pain point for Fixed
Reference Points is for people

494
00:27:58.676 --> 00:28:02.580
with any degree of vision loss
who use magnification or users

495
00:28:02.613 --> 00:28:09.187
with dyslexia who are using
special CSS sheets to reformat

496
00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:13.458
the text, to put better spacing
in or to turn off justification.

497
00:28:13.491 --> 00:28:17.195
And what happens is when you
magnify it or when you add

498
00:28:17.228 --> 00:28:20.998
additional spacing, all your
page numbering goes to heck.

499
00:28:21.031 --> 00:28:25.470
So if you are in a classroom
setting or in a legal reference

500
00:28:25.503 --> 00:28:29.040
setting, somebody
says, "I'm on page 37."

501
00:28:29.073 --> 00:28:32.744
For you, it might be page
53 because you've added that

502
00:28:32.777 --> 00:28:35.747
spacing or you've added that
magnification and the page

503
00:28:35.780 --> 00:28:38.082
numbers have totally
gotten out of sync.

504
00:28:38.115 --> 00:28:41.686
So you need to make sure that
when you're on your table of

505
00:28:41.719 --> 00:28:46.524
contents, and it says this
section starts on page 37,

506
00:28:46.557 --> 00:28:51.562
if it's really on page 53 on
your--what you're looking at,

507
00:28:51.595 --> 00:28:53.564
that when you
click on that link,

508
00:28:53.597 --> 00:28:58.836
it takes you to page 53 and
it doesn't take you to page 37

509
00:28:58.869 --> 00:29:02.473
absolutes, because that's not
the information that

510
00:29:02.506 --> 00:29:04.142
you're looking for.

511
00:29:04.175 --> 00:29:08.079
So there have to be fixed
reference points so that people

512
00:29:08.112 --> 00:29:12.617
can get to what it is that they
need to see in their environment

513
00:29:12.650 --> 00:29:15.186
that matches what
somebody else is looking at it,

514
00:29:15.219 --> 00:29:18.456
even if the page
numbers are different.

515
00:29:18.489 --> 00:29:23.294
In the next item that's being
added is for drag and drop.

516
00:29:23.327 --> 00:29:27.031
All drag and drop operations
need to be accessible

517
00:29:27.064 --> 00:29:28.432
from the keyboard.

518
00:29:28.465 --> 00:29:31.235
To me, that's kind of
a "duh" requirement.

519
00:29:31.268 --> 00:29:35.439
I felt that it was a miss in
the previous visions of WCAG.

520
00:29:35.472 --> 00:29:39.310
Inaccessible drag and drop
had to be flagged as a keyboard

521
00:29:39.343 --> 00:29:42.814
violation, and somewhat
of a pillar violation,

522
00:29:42.847 --> 00:29:46.117
in that something wasn't
operable by people using

523
00:29:46.150 --> 00:29:48.352
assistive technology.

524
00:29:48.385 --> 00:29:51.489
If you're looking for how to
implement accessible drag and

525
00:29:51.522 --> 00:29:55.493
drop, Salesforce Lightning which
is an open source design system,

526
00:29:55.526 --> 00:29:58.629
has good accessible
drag-and-drop patterns,

527
00:29:58.662 --> 00:30:02.400
and I've linked to an article
that explains how to

528
00:30:02.433 --> 00:30:03.568
implement them.

529
00:30:03.601 --> 00:30:07.305
The Clarity Design System
which is at clarity.design,

530
00:30:07.338 --> 00:30:10.474
it's one of the--it's the design
system that comes from VMware

531
00:30:10.507 --> 00:30:14.779
that I work go on, will be
having accessible drag and drop

532
00:30:14.812 --> 00:30:18.349
in a soon-to-be-released version.

533
00:30:18.382 --> 00:30:23.487
It will probably come out
before WCAG 2.2 comes out.

534
00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:27.091
And each one of these items, I
think I may have mentioned it,

535
00:30:27.124 --> 00:30:30.294
but just in case I didn't, these
are all links to the

536
00:30:30.327 --> 00:30:31.796
currently proposed text.

537
00:30:31.829 --> 00:30:35.399
You can see that there will be
comments in that saying

538
00:30:35.432 --> 00:30:37.602
open issues that need
to be addressed.

539
00:30:37.635 --> 00:30:41.606
I've just tried to translate the
spirit of the requirement

540
00:30:41.639 --> 00:30:43.441
into English on these pages.

541
00:30:43.474 --> 00:30:50.248
So 3.2.7 to me, like 2.5.7,
was something that was

542
00:30:50.281 --> 00:30:52.350
kind of a miss.

543
00:30:52.383 --> 00:30:56.354
It could be implied that
there was a keyboard operation

544
00:30:56.387 --> 00:31:00.791
violation, which that
requirement didn't actually work

545
00:31:00.824 --> 00:31:03.060
for mobile.

546
00:31:03.093 --> 00:31:08.366
So, for example, you
could have a hidden control,

547
00:31:08.399 --> 00:31:11.702
for example, a swipe left
to delete in a native app,

548
00:31:11.735 --> 00:31:17.308
and there was really no
guideline in WCAG 2.1

549
00:31:17.341 --> 00:31:18.709
that made that illegal.

550
00:31:18.742 --> 00:31:21.445
And you have to remember
not everybody can touch

551
00:31:21.478 --> 00:31:23.114
their device.

552
00:31:23.147 --> 00:31:24.849
Not everybody can
use a keyboard,

553
00:31:24.882 --> 00:31:30.321
so you need to have a way from
the keyboard to trigger hidden

554
00:31:30.354 --> 00:31:35.726
operations which then, Sip and
Puff devices and switch devices

555
00:31:35.759 --> 00:31:39.864
use keyboard simulation to
order--in order to access those,

556
00:31:39.897 --> 00:31:44.235
even though the user still
is never touching a keyboard.

557
00:31:44.268 --> 00:31:47.772
So swipe left to delete in
a native app is where

558
00:31:47.805 --> 00:31:50.341
hidden controls are most common.

559
00:31:50.374 --> 00:31:53.711
Advancing controls for a
manual slide carousels.

560
00:31:53.744 --> 00:31:58.649
So if you have a carousel
that doesn't automatically move,

561
00:31:58.682 --> 00:32:02.219
and it's got arrows that only
come up when you mouse

562
00:32:02.252 --> 00:32:05.022
over to them, those controls
are considered hidden.

563
00:32:05.055 --> 00:32:09.593
So you need to have a keyboard
controls or they have to be

564
00:32:09.626 --> 00:32:11.595
visible without requiring cover.

565
00:32:11.628 --> 00:32:14.231
So another way you
could do it is making them

566
00:32:14.264 --> 00:32:17.201
persistently visible.

567
00:32:17.234 --> 00:32:19.236
How do you make them
persistently visible?

568
00:32:19.269 --> 00:32:22.340
You could make that a feature
that's associated with the

569
00:32:22.373 --> 00:32:27.478
login, so that would come under
personalization where you could

570
00:32:27.511 --> 00:32:31.515
have somebody set up things
in their accounts saying,

571
00:32:31.548 --> 00:32:34.085
"I want closed close captioning
turned on all the time.

572
00:32:34.118 --> 00:32:36.854
I want all hidden controls
visible all the time.

573
00:32:36.887 --> 00:32:39.657
I always want to use a
dyslexia friendly font."

574
00:32:39.690 --> 00:32:43.127
Accessibility features that you
could associate with the login,

575
00:32:43.160 --> 00:32:46.464
so that once the user logs
in, all those features get

576
00:32:46.497 --> 00:32:49.100
set automatically.

577
00:32:49.133 --> 00:32:53.571
Okay, Pointer Target Spacing is
another add-on from WCAG 2.1.

578
00:32:53.604 --> 00:32:58.075
2.1 had a guideline for
what they called inadvertent

579
00:32:58.108 --> 00:33:02.113
activation, but it
didn't have a spacing.

580
00:33:02.146 --> 00:33:07.451
So that gave us a guideline of
minimum size of 44 CSS pixels

581
00:33:07.484 --> 00:33:09.787
squared, but it
didn't talk about spacing.

582
00:33:09.820 --> 00:33:11.422
Okay.

583
00:33:11.455 --> 00:33:13.424
So this addresses the
spacing requirement.

584
00:33:13.457 --> 00:33:18.396
So it expands on the 2.1
requirement pertaining

585
00:33:18.429 --> 00:33:20.498
to the size.

586
00:33:20.531 --> 00:33:23.267
And also in--this was
one thing that really

587
00:33:23.300 --> 00:33:24.769
frustrated me in 2.1.

588
00:33:24.802 --> 00:33:26.804
I lost the vote on this one.

589
00:33:26.837 --> 00:33:29.807
Originally, it was proposed
to be a AA requirement and the

590
00:33:29.840 --> 00:33:33.778
minimum touch target size
became a AAA requirement,

591
00:33:33.811 --> 00:33:36.647
which meant really nobody
was obligated to implement it.

592
00:33:36.680 --> 00:33:41.052
This Pointer Target Spacing
guideline is a AA requirement,

593
00:33:41.085 --> 00:33:43.854
so people will be obligated,
for the most part,

594
00:33:43.887 --> 00:33:45.689
to implement that.

595
00:33:45.722 --> 00:33:48.426
Hey, then there are
three new guidelines in

596
00:33:48.459 --> 00:33:51.462
WCAG 2.2 that pertain to Silver.

597
00:33:51.495 --> 00:33:55.699
One is Finding Help, one is
Accessible Authentication,

598
00:33:55.732 --> 00:33:58.235
and one is Redundant Entry.

599
00:33:58.268 --> 00:34:01.806
And you can see all three of
these are A-level requirements,

600
00:34:01.839 --> 00:34:04.708
because you're blocking an
entire group of people with

601
00:34:04.741 --> 00:34:08.379
cognitive disabilities from
being able to interact with

602
00:34:08.412 --> 00:34:10.347
your site or your software,
if you're not doing

603
00:34:10.380 --> 00:34:12.383
these three things.

604
00:34:12.416 --> 00:34:13.617
Okay.

605
00:34:13.651 --> 00:34:17.688
So Findable Help, every single
page has to have help available

606
00:34:17.721 --> 00:34:21.459
somewhere, okay, either how
to get in touch with a human;

607
00:34:21.492 --> 00:34:24.228
how to contact the human, so
a phone number or an email

608
00:34:24.261 --> 00:34:29.366
address; a self-help option, so
context sensitive help for that

609
00:34:29.399 --> 00:34:33.204
page; or a fully
automated contact mechanism.

610
00:34:33.237 --> 00:34:38.309
So you need to have one of those
minimum on every single page.

611
00:34:38.342 --> 00:34:40.544
You know,
probably in the footer.

612
00:34:40.577 --> 00:34:43.547
Although, WCAG is not
prescriptive about how you do,

613
00:34:43.580 --> 00:34:46.050
how you implement
the guidelines,

614
00:34:46.083 --> 00:34:49.453
just that the guidelines
have to be implemented.

615
00:34:49.486 --> 00:34:51.822
Accessible Authentication.

616
00:34:51.855 --> 00:34:55.526
So authentication
meaning logging in,

617
00:34:55.559 --> 00:34:58.696
if it requires on a
cognitive function test,

618
00:34:58.729 --> 00:35:02.366
you also have to have another
method that doesn't rely on

619
00:35:02.399 --> 00:35:04.101
a cognitive function test.

620
00:35:04.134 --> 00:35:07.404
Memory, which includes
remembering a password,

621
00:35:07.437 --> 00:35:10.174
is considered a
cognitive function test.

622
00:35:10.207 --> 00:35:14.512
So that means that to be
compliant with WCAG 2.2,

623
00:35:14.545 --> 00:35:17.014
at the A-level, you're going
to have to have at least

624
00:35:17.047 --> 00:35:18.549
two methods of being
able to log in.

625
00:35:18.582 --> 00:35:22.353
The standard username and
password and some type of

626
00:35:22.386 --> 00:35:26.557
secondary login, such as
biometrics or sending a link

627
00:35:26.590 --> 00:35:33.030
or a code to a registered phone,
so that somebody who has memory

628
00:35:33.063 --> 00:35:35.199
issues and can't
remember their passwords,

629
00:35:35.232 --> 00:35:38.769
still has a secure
way of getting in.

630
00:35:39.303 --> 00:35:40.604
Okay.

631
00:35:40.637 --> 00:35:46.076
WCAG, the next one,
Redundant Entry.

632
00:35:46.109 --> 00:35:48.812
This is one of my pet peeves.

633
00:35:48.845 --> 00:35:50.848
I'm so glad that they
implemented this feature,

634
00:35:50.881 --> 00:35:53.217
because to me, this
happens all the time.

635
00:35:53.250 --> 00:35:56.287
So you try to log in on
something that you haven't seen

636
00:35:56.320 --> 00:36:01.759
in a year, the login fails, you
press "forget password" to reset

637
00:36:01.792 --> 00:36:05.563
your password and it asks
you to type your login again.

638
00:36:05.596 --> 00:36:07.698
It had the login.

639
00:36:07.731 --> 00:36:10.434
Your already put it in
when you tried to log in.

640
00:36:10.467 --> 00:36:14.071
The website had the information,
but it's making you

641
00:36:14.104 --> 00:36:15.305
type it in twice.

642
00:36:15.339 --> 00:36:19.043
It takes a long time for people
with disabilities to enter in

643
00:36:19.076 --> 00:36:23.180
things, especially when they're
using assistive technology.

644
00:36:23.213 --> 00:36:29.053
So making people type things
twice is not satisfying

645
00:36:29.086 --> 00:36:31.055
the spirit of being accessible.

646
00:36:31.088 --> 00:36:35.526
Failing to implement auto
population is not following

647
00:36:35.559 --> 00:36:37.428
the spirit of being accessible.

648
00:36:37.461 --> 00:36:41.732
So do two things are going to be
part of WCAG 2.2 under

649
00:36:41.765 --> 00:36:47.838
Redundant Entry which
is part of COGA.

650
00:36:47.871 --> 00:36:52.142
And then finally,
where are we on 2.2?

651
00:36:52.175 --> 00:36:53.744
The Second Public
Working Draft is out.

652
00:36:53.777 --> 00:36:56.580
It's anticipated to be
final by next summer.

653
00:36:56.613 --> 00:37:00.618
And as I mentioned, in the U.S.,
that means you're going to have

654
00:37:00.651 --> 00:37:06.624
about 18 months before you
get in trouble in terms

655
00:37:06.657 --> 00:37:09.293
of litigation.

656
00:37:09.326 --> 00:37:11.028
I'll quickly go through Silver.

657
00:37:11.061 --> 00:37:13.530
As I've mentioned, Silver
is the next evolution in

658
00:37:13.563 --> 00:37:17.134
the W3C guidelines.

659
00:37:17.167 --> 00:37:20.304
We took--and the Silver name
came from the idea that it was

660
00:37:20.337 --> 00:37:22.706
just going to be called
Accessibility Guidelines,

661
00:37:22.739 --> 00:37:26.143
but we took a vote and we
decided to leave the WC

662
00:37:26.176 --> 00:37:28.312
in because it's what
people are familiar with.

663
00:37:28.345 --> 00:37:32.483
So Silver is WCAG 3.0.

664
00:37:32.516 --> 00:37:36.186
It's more of a focus on
functional need than

665
00:37:36.219 --> 00:37:37.454
is on guidelines.

666
00:37:37.487 --> 00:37:41.225
So, for example, remember those
three different guidelines that

667
00:37:41.258 --> 00:37:44.461
pertained to
keyboard focus indicators?

668
00:37:44.494 --> 00:37:46.463
Those are all going to
be grouped together.

669
00:37:46.496 --> 00:37:49.233
I'm responsible for something
that's being called

670
00:37:49.266 --> 00:37:50.401
content structure.

671
00:37:50.434 --> 00:37:53.604
Content structure will be
the three different heading

672
00:37:53.637 --> 00:37:56.206
guidelines that currently
exist grouped together.

673
00:37:56.239 --> 00:37:59.677
In terms of scoring, there will
be a scoring function of how

674
00:37:59.710 --> 00:38:03.981
compliant you are, which is
going to be more of a focus on

675
00:38:04.014 --> 00:38:06.383
being substantively conformant.

676
00:38:06.416 --> 00:38:10.087
Right now, as the
VPATs and WCAG stands,

677
00:38:10.120 --> 00:38:15.025
if you have 5000 pieces of alt
text and you have one little,

678
00:38:15.058 --> 00:38:19.063
teeny piece away in a corner
that's not working correctly,

679
00:38:19.096 --> 00:38:21.365
you're considered
to be noncompliant.

680
00:38:21.398 --> 00:38:25.469
Here, the focus is on the
absolutes of compliance

681
00:38:25.502 --> 00:38:27.137
versus noncompliance.

682
00:38:27.170 --> 00:38:29.673
It's more focused on can
a user with a disability

683
00:38:29.706 --> 00:38:31.809
use this software?

684
00:38:31.842 --> 00:38:34.578
And there's also going to be
completely brand-new areas

685
00:38:34.611 --> 00:38:39.016
of guidance, one
will be on VR and XR,

686
00:38:39.049 --> 00:38:42.186
so virtual reality
and extended reality.

687
00:38:42.219 --> 00:38:44.755
And another area that's being
added is maturity modeling.

688
00:38:44.788 --> 00:38:47.358
This isn't intended to
be an exhaustive list,

689
00:38:47.391 --> 00:38:50.794
just to give you an idea of what
types of things are coming in

690
00:38:50.827 --> 00:38:54.832
Silver and where it's going to
be different than the versions of

691
00:38:54.865 --> 00:39:00.704
WCAG that we've had since 2006.

692
00:39:00.737 --> 00:39:02.206
Okay.

693
00:39:02.239 --> 00:39:03.374
So resource summary at the end.

694
00:39:03.407 --> 00:39:08.078
These are all of the guidelines
that are coming with 2.2.

695
00:39:08.111 --> 00:39:11.415
And I am happy at this point to
take any questions that Amber,

696
00:39:11.448 --> 00:39:14.318
I believe, is going to pass
those to me from

697
00:39:14.351 --> 00:39:16.987
the YouTube feed.

698
00:39:17.020 --> 00:39:18.322
<v Amber> Yeah.

699
00:39:18.355 --> 00:39:19.723
<v Sheri> And I'm going
to drink some coffee.

700
00:39:19.756 --> 00:39:21.225
<v Amber> Well,
thank you so much.

701
00:39:21.258 --> 00:39:22.459
That was very informative.

702
00:39:22.493 --> 00:39:26.263
There are quite a few questions
here about how you got started

703
00:39:26.296 --> 00:39:28.132
and volunteering.

704
00:39:28.165 --> 00:39:29.666
Volunteering.

705
00:39:29.699 --> 00:39:31.702
Can you share a little bit about
your background and what got

706
00:39:31.735 --> 00:39:34.271
you interested in this?

707
00:39:34.304 --> 00:39:35.606
<v Sheri> Sure.

708
00:39:35.639 --> 00:39:38.475
So I'm what I like to
call really overeducated.

709
00:39:38.508 --> 00:39:42.212
I started off, let's just say
more than three decades ago

710
00:39:42.245 --> 00:39:44.415
with a degree in
computer science.

711
00:39:44.448 --> 00:39:47.751
I went to CAL in the early '80s.

712
00:39:47.784 --> 00:39:52.523
Then ten years after that, I
decided that I wanted to go

713
00:39:52.556 --> 00:39:54.191
to law school.

714
00:39:54.224 --> 00:39:57.027
My third year of law school,
we discovered that by middle

715
00:39:57.060 --> 00:39:59.163
daughter was losing her hearing.

716
00:39:59.196 --> 00:40:01.365
She had a
progressive hearing loss.

717
00:40:01.398 --> 00:40:05.035
So I had intended to go
the anesthesiology of law,

718
00:40:05.068 --> 00:40:08.338
which is intellectual property,
especially because I live

719
00:40:08.371 --> 00:40:09.740
in Silicon Valley.

720
00:40:09.773 --> 00:40:12.276
I was doing things like
trademarks and copyrights

721
00:40:12.309 --> 00:40:13.644
and patents.

722
00:40:13.677 --> 00:40:17.347
I ended up going into
advocacy for the deaf instead.

723
00:40:17.380 --> 00:40:19.716
And so I did that
for eight years.

724
00:40:19.749 --> 00:40:23.287
And then, basically put myself
out of business because I was

725
00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:26.190
suing insurance companies
for failing to provide equal

726
00:40:26.223 --> 00:40:28.859
treatment for deaf patients.

727
00:40:28.892 --> 00:40:32.062
And I won a class action
lawsuit against Blue Cross,

728
00:40:32.095 --> 00:40:33.864
and everybody folded.

729
00:40:33.897 --> 00:40:35.766
And I was doing it
through a nonprofit anyway,

730
00:40:35.799 --> 00:40:39.102
so it wasn't exactly like I was
making money hand over fist

731
00:40:39.135 --> 00:40:41.071
with these lawsuits.

732
00:40:41.104 --> 00:40:44.675
So I needed to pivot again, and
that was just when accessibility

733
00:40:44.708 --> 00:40:46.677
was really starting to take off.

734
00:40:46.710 --> 00:40:49.179
That was about eight years
ago, and I've been in

735
00:40:49.212 --> 00:40:50.881
digital accessibility
ever since.

736
00:40:50.914 --> 00:40:54.585
So I think it makes, it's a
really nice intersection

737
00:40:54.618 --> 00:40:56.687
of what I love to do the most.

738
00:40:56.720 --> 00:41:01.225
It's tech, because if
some developer says,

739
00:41:01.258 --> 00:41:03.594
"Oh, that's going to be hard."

740
00:41:03.627 --> 00:41:06.430
My response is always,
"Would you like me to code

741
00:41:06.463 --> 00:41:07.664
that for you?"

742
00:41:07.698 --> 00:41:12.202
I mean I can actually tell when
they're trying to avoid doing

743
00:41:12.235 --> 00:41:16.807
something just because
they don't want to do it.

744
00:41:16.840 --> 00:41:20.277
You know, I use my legal
degree to interpret the laws.

745
00:41:20.310 --> 00:41:22.779
And then, I also went
back and got an MBA,

746
00:41:22.812 --> 00:41:25.215
so I also see the business
perspective of accessibility

747
00:41:25.248 --> 00:41:28.151
and I could write really
strong business cases for it.

748
00:41:28.184 --> 00:41:31.188
So people automatically
assume that because I've used

749
00:41:31.221 --> 00:41:33.824
a wheelchair since I was five,
that that's why I got

750
00:41:33.857 --> 00:41:35.392
into accessibility.

751
00:41:35.425 --> 00:41:36.727
But I actually got into
accessibility because

752
00:41:36.760 --> 00:41:37.961
of my deaf daughter.

753
00:41:37.995 --> 00:41:41.098
To me, my wheelchair is just a
mechanism of getting around.

754
00:41:41.131 --> 00:41:44.468
I don't particularly
consider that a disability.

755
00:41:44.501 --> 00:41:47.104
And then what was
the second question?

756
00:41:47.137 --> 00:41:48.772
The second question
was about volunteering?

757
00:41:48.805 --> 00:41:49.940
<v Amber> Yes.

758
00:41:49.973 --> 00:41:52.676
So there's a couple of people
who have asked what kind

759
00:41:52.709 --> 00:41:56.647
of tasks do people participate
in, in W3C Task Forces?

760
00:41:56.680 --> 00:41:59.449
What are the tasks
that they end up doing?

761
00:41:59.482 --> 00:42:02.319
What is the
volunteer experience like?

762
00:42:02.352 --> 00:42:03.553
<v Sheri> Sure.

763
00:42:03.587 --> 00:42:06.423
So like I said, lots, and lots,
and lots and lots of meetings,

764
00:42:06.456 --> 00:42:10.227
and a little bit of take away
and go and do some research

765
00:42:10.260 --> 00:42:11.662
on your own.

766
00:42:11.695 --> 00:42:14.765
So, for example on the Maturity
Modeling Subcommittee which

767
00:42:14.798 --> 00:42:18.702
I co-lead with David Fazio,
right now what we're doing is we

768
00:42:18.735 --> 00:42:22.339
have built a framework of
dimensions and attributes,

769
00:42:22.372 --> 00:42:26.443
and everybody on the
team has one dimension,

770
00:42:26.476 --> 00:42:29.613
and they are defining all
the different attributes.

771
00:42:29.646 --> 00:42:34.518
So we are proposing, and
this hasn't even been reviewed.

772
00:42:34.551 --> 00:42:37.187
I have to be a little bit vague
here because it hasn't been

773
00:42:37.220 --> 00:42:40.057
reviewed by the
Silver subcommittee yet.

774
00:42:40.090 --> 00:42:42.326
That's happening
in about a month.

775
00:42:42.359 --> 00:42:45.596
But everybody has been
assigned one of those things.

776
00:42:45.629 --> 00:42:48.865
So we go in, we put in straw man
information about what we think

777
00:42:48.898 --> 00:42:51.868
the attribute should look
like for that dimension.

778
00:42:51.901 --> 00:42:53.670
So let me give you an example.

779
00:42:53.703 --> 00:42:56.273
For a dimension of
software development lifecycle,

780
00:42:56.306 --> 00:43:01.044
it might include an attribute of
you have a software QA plan that

781
00:43:01.077 --> 00:43:04.314
references accessibility
and assistive technology.

782
00:43:04.347 --> 00:43:07.017
And then we get together and
we meet as a group and we talk

783
00:43:07.050 --> 00:43:11.588
about each other's work, and we
wordsmith it so that in the end,

784
00:43:11.621 --> 00:43:16.259
it all looks like it was written
with one cohesive approach by

785
00:43:16.292 --> 00:43:19.796
one individual, instead of
actually being worked on by

786
00:43:19.829 --> 00:43:21.832
six or eight different
individuals, because that's

787
00:43:21.865 --> 00:43:24.801
really important
to the end product.

788
00:43:24.834 --> 00:43:28.639
So meetings to
discuss what's going on.

789
00:43:28.672 --> 00:43:34.378
We all work in Google Docs
together and put in comments

790
00:43:34.411 --> 00:43:36.146
about each other's work.

791
00:43:36.179 --> 00:43:39.683
We've refined the comments, then
the Maturity Model Subcommittee

792
00:43:39.716 --> 00:43:42.319
takes that and reviews it
with the Silver Committee.

793
00:43:42.352 --> 00:43:44.421
Once it's approved by
the Silver Committee,

794
00:43:44.454 --> 00:43:47.391
then we take it up to
the--what they call the AG WG,

795
00:43:47.424 --> 00:43:50.193
the Accessibility
Guidelines Working Group.

796
00:43:50.226 --> 00:43:53.697
Once it gets approved by them,
then it gets published

797
00:43:53.730 --> 00:43:58.468
for people, for the general
community to comment on.

798
00:43:58.501 --> 00:44:04.141
And at any time, somebody who
is identified as a volunteer

799
00:44:04.174 --> 00:44:08.045
can look at any of the
draft material in GitHub.

800
00:44:08.078 --> 00:44:12.082
We use Git for versioning all
of our documents and

801
00:44:12.115 --> 00:44:14.351
that's where we release from.

802
00:44:14.384 --> 00:44:17.320
So hopefully that
answers your question.

803
00:44:17.353 --> 00:44:18.655
<v Amber> What's
the time commitment?

804
00:44:18.688 --> 00:44:21.291
<v Sheri> And like
I said the first--

805
00:44:21.324 --> 00:44:22.626
<v Amber> I'm sorry.

806
00:44:22.659 --> 00:44:24.327
<v Sheri> Minimum time
commitment is--yeah,

807
00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:25.561
that's all right.

808
00:44:25.595 --> 00:44:28.031
No, minimum time commitment
is probably practically about

809
00:44:28.064 --> 00:44:29.433
six hours a week.

810
00:44:29.466 --> 00:44:31.068
<v Amber> Okay.

811
00:44:31.101 --> 00:44:34.337
<v Sheri> It's not for people
who just want to pop in now

812
00:44:34.370 --> 00:44:37.307
and then and see
what's going on.

813
00:44:37.340 --> 00:44:42.813
It is definitely a
significant amount of time.

814
00:44:42.846 --> 00:44:44.347
<v Amber> Good to know.

815
00:44:44.380 --> 00:44:46.416
What's the best way--someone
asked what's the best way

816
00:44:46.449 --> 00:44:51.822
to build yourself
into a WCAG expert?

817
00:44:51.855 --> 00:44:53.557
<v Sheri> What's the best way?

818
00:44:53.590 --> 00:44:58.361
So, I would say
for starters, IAAP,

819
00:44:58.394 --> 00:45:02.099
the International Association
of Accessibility Professionals

820
00:45:02.132 --> 00:45:06.703
has two certification programs
right now and they're about

821
00:45:06.736 --> 00:45:08.438
to add several more.

822
00:45:08.471 --> 00:45:12.375
So there is the CPACC,
which is Certified Professional

823
00:45:12.408 --> 00:45:15.445
Accessibility Core Competencies.

824
00:45:15.478 --> 00:45:17.481
That's for lack of
a better phrase.

825
00:45:17.514 --> 00:45:20.317
The Accessibility
Manager certification.

826
00:45:20.350 --> 00:45:24.554
Then there's the WAS,
which is the Web Accessibility

827
00:45:24.587 --> 00:45:26.223
Specialist certification.

828
00:45:26.256 --> 00:45:28.425
That requires
significant coding chops.

829
00:45:28.458 --> 00:45:32.529
And then the third certification
that's coming is

830
00:45:32.562 --> 00:45:34.164
Strategic Leader
in Accessibility.

831
00:45:34.197 --> 00:45:38.101
So that's people who are looking
at implementing accessibility

832
00:45:38.134 --> 00:45:40.504
at the organizational level.

833
00:45:40.537 --> 00:45:42.339
How do you set up
training programs?

834
00:45:42.372 --> 00:45:44.141
How do you set up
support programs?

835
00:45:44.174 --> 00:45:47.144
How do you may sure your
documentation is accessible?

836
00:45:47.177 --> 00:45:52.549
So certifying through those
groups definitely demonstrates

837
00:45:52.582 --> 00:45:58.421
that you have a particular
level of accessibility skills.

838
00:45:58.454 --> 00:46:01.424
I write a lot.

839
00:46:01.457 --> 00:46:04.161
I've been writing twice a
week now for two years.

840
00:46:04.194 --> 00:46:08.698
I'm up to, I think, 154 articles
when I counted last week,

841
00:46:08.731 --> 00:46:12.435
on various different
approaches to accessibility.

842
00:46:12.468 --> 00:46:16.439
So the last article that I
wrote was about making sure that

843
00:46:16.472 --> 00:46:20.477
people use context when they're
identifying what their alt text

844
00:46:20.510 --> 00:46:22.078
should be.

845
00:46:22.111 --> 00:46:25.816
So that's a way that you
can demonstrate your

846
00:46:25.849 --> 00:46:28.018
accessibility skills.

847
00:46:28.051 --> 00:46:31.288
I think building your
accessibility brand on

848
00:46:31.321 --> 00:46:33.089
social media is
really important.

849
00:46:33.122 --> 00:46:35.058
I wrote an article on that.

850
00:46:35.091 --> 00:46:39.129
You definitely need to have an
accessibility elevator pitch

851
00:46:39.162 --> 00:46:43.433
so you can explain in 45 seconds
what is it that you as

852
00:46:43.466 --> 00:46:47.137
an individual bring to an
accessibility program.

853
00:46:47.170 --> 00:46:51.141
So those things are all.

854
00:46:51.174 --> 00:46:55.378
And then, obviously doing
presentations like this,

855
00:46:55.411 --> 00:46:58.348
and preferably recorded
presentations so that people can

856
00:46:58.381 --> 00:47:00.250
get them on demand.

857
00:47:00.283 --> 00:47:06.156
That--so I submitted
seven presentations to

858
00:47:06.189 --> 00:47:09.192
seven different conferences
a couple months ago.

859
00:47:09.225 --> 00:47:14.130
Usually about 50% of my
presentations get accepted.

860
00:47:14.163 --> 00:47:17.100
For some reason, six out
of seven got accepted,

861
00:47:17.133 --> 00:47:21.504
so I've been really busy
giving talks this month,

862
00:47:21.537 --> 00:47:25.442
but that's another aspect to
building your accessibility

863
00:47:25.475 --> 00:47:30.313
brand, of people being able to
watch recorded presentations.

864
00:47:30.346 --> 00:47:32.515
<v Amber> Well, we really
appreciate you coming

865
00:47:32.548 --> 00:47:34.651
and sharing all the
information with us.

866
00:47:34.684 --> 00:47:37.287
Those are all the questions
we have time for today.

867
00:47:37.320 --> 00:47:39.789
But I'm sure that if you
have additional questions,

868
00:47:39.822 --> 00:47:43.627
you can reach out to Sheri via
the information that she has

869
00:47:43.660 --> 00:47:47.764
shared on the slides
or via her Medium blog.

870
00:47:47.797 --> 00:47:49.833
Don't forget to
attend the next talk.

871
00:47:49.866 --> 00:47:51.334
<v Sheri> Just--

872
00:47:51.367 --> 00:47:52.669
<v Amber> Oh, yeah.

873
00:47:52.702 --> 00:47:54.170
<v Sheri> Oh, sorry.

874
00:47:54.203 --> 00:47:55.772
I was just going to say drop
me a--on LinkedIn,

875
00:47:55.805 --> 00:48:00.744
that's a social media that I pay
most attention to or put a note

876
00:48:00.777 --> 00:48:03.513
in one of my articles on Medium.

877
00:48:03.546 --> 00:48:05.349
<v Amber> Okay.
Well, thank you so much, Sheri.
